review_blob: Purchased six pack from LCBO; this was packaged with a maple beer but I didnt get to try that one.  Nonetheless, this was solid beer, probably not the best example of a doppelbock though a welcome addition to the Mill street line.

Bought a couple of six packs. Green bottles, wasnt expecting great aroma but it was actually nice toasty caramel.  Colour a little lighter than I was expecting. Flavour was good enough but wanted more especially since its an amber ale from Amsterdam.  Pretty good overall but nothing to write home about.
beer_name: Amsterdam Big Wheel Deluxe Amber Beer

review_blob: Again, another beer from the Sam Adams holiday pack. This is mahogany with a tan head, with a nice toasty chocolatey aroma. Very smooth and creamy, well rounded.  If any complaint is its cocoa can be overpowering at timesfor my liking but during the winter, I dont mind.

Last bottle from Sam Adams holiday variety pack thing.... Nice spicy aroma, clear cloudy gold colour. Flavour wise has a little bit too much going on for my liking. However, still an enjoyable Witbier especially for the holidays, which are long gone at this point.
Bottle from last year, think its still good. Nice earthy woodsy aroma; beautiful deep copper colour & rich robust flavour. Yeah, I think its still good.

Got this as part of the Mcauslan holiday gift pack from last year. Its almost winter again but should have drank this back in the summer, wouldve made a great summer beer.  Very good buttery fruity aroma, almost like a peach cobbler. Fruity taste is subtle; overall a great wheat beer.

Had this beer at Duke of Devon not really knowing what it was except that its supposedly a Belgian white.  Well, its not the best example of a Belgian white thats for sure.  Mine had almost an artificial orange colour, and same with the taste.  Like someone mixed a bud light with a bit of orange crush soda. If you want a mass produced Belgian white stick with Blue Moon, better yet, get a real one form Unibroue or something actually from Belgium.

Got this beer as part of the McAuslan holiday gift pack last year.  Pours dark amber with tan head, nice clean aroma.  Robust and quite smooth; not a bad pale ale. Its not quite up there with my favourite; Tankhouse ale.
500ml cans from LCBO; bought a bunch for last St. Pattys day.  Nothing special; typical macro lager. Better than the typical Molbatts stuff out there as it has some body and doesnt taste like water.

6-pack from my bro in the States.  Cant really find this here in Ontario, shame.  Pours mahogany with a nice tan head.  Aroma is quite nice and crisp; fruity & earthy at the same time.  Bold flavours with nice clean finish. Overall a solid beer.
12 pack from bro earlier this year; finally down to my last one which to rate.  Pours a dark bronze with a tan head.  Decent aroma and taste; not a bad winter ale but there are better ones.

Bottle from last year from my bro.  Sat in my cooler/fridge for a year and it was still good.  The first 4 bottles I drank when I first got them.  Either way it was one of the best stouts Ive had. Nice ink black colour, excellent aroma and flavour. One more bottle sitting in my fridge. Woo!

Six pack from LCBO. Amber colour, nice head on pour that dissipates quickly. Fruity citrus aroma; a little hint of metallic - maybe its just me.  Taste ok a little thin, finishes well though.  Solid if not spectacular Vienna.
Six pack from LCBO. Pours cloudy golden, very nice hoppy aroma.  Nice balance of malt & hops. Solid pilsner.

12 pack from my bro, thanks! Pours golden, with a short lived white head.  Sweet citrus aroma and tastes just a sweet; at least it lives up to its honey moniker.  Actually, the taste kinda reminded me of peanut butter with honey.  Not too bad but a little on the sweet side for my liking.
beer_name: Blue Moon Honey Moon Summer Ale

review_blob: Bought a bunch of six packs for a party this summer.  Nothing too bad or good about this beer.  Just a run of the mill below average macro. Ill take it over a Blue or Bud but that aint sayin much.

Bottle from my bro after returning from NYC.  Great amber appearance; tan head that lasts and leaves lacing.  Nice fruity/flowery aroma. Starts off well, nice dark malty flavour and perfect hops in the finish.  Great balance.  Overall a excellent beer, one of my favourites.

2011 edition 6 pack given by my bro from the states - thanks! Beautiful golden colour with nice head that lasts.  Typical grassy / hop aroma nothing special.  Nice malty start with great hops in the finish, nicely balanced - overall good taste.  A great late spring / early summer beer
Last bottle from Cleveland trip. Nothing exciting but Apricot flavour works with the balanced malt and slight bitter finish.  Mine had a slight buttery taste and aroma. Refreshing late summer beer.
Six pack bought while visiting my bro in Ohio.  An excellent example of a German Hefeweizen, just as good if not better then the ones from Germany.  Great job Sierra Nevada!

6 pack bottles from bro.  Pours amber with short lived tan head some lacing. Grainy & grassy aroma nothing special.  Taste is about the same as well; actually I found it a tad watery.  Not bad but nothing stands out about it either.  Pretty average beer.

Thx to my bro and sis-in-law returning from Kansas. The only one in the 12-pack sampler I havent tried yet. Nice golden colour, small head some lacing. Faint aroma of citrus and caramel.  Taste is alright; lingering hops in the finish.  Pretty solid.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Bottle from six pack thanks to my bro.  Dark copper pour; pretty nice actually. Fruity aroma, with a hint of nut. Taste is a tad on the watery side but its got nice hints of malt and fruit throughout.  Its straight forward, at least for this type of ale (if that makes any sense).  Nothing special but clean tasting and not boring or offensive. Solid if not spectacular.
Bottle from 6 pack, from bro in States.  Thanks. Pours a murky amber, tan head.  Fruity aroma and also quite woodsy.  Roasted malt flavour balanced out with a nice hoppy finish. Not bad.

Six pack from LCBO.  Blonde colour (duh), small white foamy head that died quickly.  A bit skunky (the clear bottles?) I think so.  Not much character and very little hops, but has a clean taste unlike a typical macro.  The definition of "easy drinking" but without the nasty.

500 ml bottle from LCBO. Nice cloudy brownish black pour, lasting tan head. Beautiful. Aroma of coffee, some roasted nuts and chocolate.  Nice roasted malty start with a bitter coffee and chocolaty finishing taste. Excellent from start to finish.
Bottle, opened with a big whiff of skunk.  After the skunk settled, it was mostly grass and sweet grain.  Pours clear yellow with a thick white head.  Grainy and corny flavour finish was weak.

330ml bottle.  Pours dark amber with soapy head.  Caramel aroma, initial taste is also caramel with a wee bit of a roasted nutty taste to it.  Finish is somewhat watery just like the Dos Equis Lager which I had previous  to this.  Better than the lager but still a little below average.
Pours pale with small white head.  Corn/grainy aroma, very little flavour.  Quite watery.  What youd expect from a Mexican pale lager.
Split several bucket-o-Coronas with some Coronas with some co-workers at Jack Astors.  Thank God for the limes that came with this or else Id this is as bland and boring as it gets.

Final beer to taste from Boulevard Sampler pack. (thanks again to my bro/sis-in-law)  This one pours blond, cloudy, small white head.  Aroma and taste is what Ive come to expect from a Wit.  This is a pretty good example of one, better than a RIckards white, though not as good as a Blanche de Chambly.

Yet another Boulevard I got to try from the sample pack, thanks again to my bro/sis-in-law, nice cloudy amber pour, large head. Very citrusy and hoppy.  Taste is what Ive come to expect from an American micro-brewed IPA.  Nice balance with a hoppy finish.  A great IPA and another great one from Boulevard.

Another bottle from the Boulevard 12-pack sampler from my bro/sis-in-law.  This one pours deep mahogany with respectable tan head.  Coffee aroma with chocolaty flavour finishing with a nice subtle bitterness. An excellent example of a great porter.

Bottle from bro/sis-in-law back from Kansas.  Pours muddy amber small tan head.  Fruity aroma, weak banana taste with some grainy and yeasty flavours throughout but a little watery overall.  Nothing special but pretty good beer.

Bottle from bro/sis-in-law back from the States.  Pours a nice amber red with a tan head and some lacing. A whiff of caramel aroma, quite sweet actually.  Same can be said for the flavour; sweet with a touch a bitterness in the end.  Nothing earth shattering but

Bottle from my bro/sis-in-law from the states.  Cant remember who gave it. Pours fine amber with small tan-ish head.  Aroma of wheat and cherry.  Very sweet.  Tasted like a fine wheat with sugary cherry added to it; the same way cherry flavouring is added to cherry coke.  Cant say Im a fan of this but it is not bad either.  It kinda grows on you and is a good summer quencher.

Bottle from my bro, who got it from my other bro.  Anyway, pours blackish brown, large tan head.  Roasted malt and dark chocolaty aroma.  Roasted nutty flavour with a distinct note of coffee.  Overall an excellent beer.  Great Lakes does it again.

Had to buy some "easy drinking" beers for my cousins baby shower last month since it was mostly ladies there.  I decided on this.  What can I say, another cheap watery beer that looks like anemic piss. The only thing going for it is that it is so thin that you dont taste anything offensive.

Six pack from LCBO, pours amber/brown, tan head. Nice roasted malty aroma.  Flavour is nutty with roasted malt and a hit a chocolate although it tasted a little burnt at times but I quite liked it.  Overall a good beer.

Tap @ the Black Hoof, with a couple a friends after a competition (Thanks Anna & Cara).  Food was awesome, but this was the perfect beer to compliment everything else.  Perfectly poured with a white head, and a citrus aroma.  Excellent palate - almost silky mouthfeel, but then again I was eating Foie Gras and Iberico.  But really, before the food came I I enjoyed the beer on its own so this rating is fair enough.  All in all, glad this place carried this beer.
On tap at Cest What. Brown colour, no head by the time the beer arrived at my table.  Aroma and flavour were lackig;  very malty not much else there.  A decent pub brew, I enjoyed it for what it was.

330ml bottle, six pack from LCBO. Pour golden with thick head.  Typically nice bready/citrus aroma.  Sweet taste with a nice balancing bitterness in the end.  An above average brew better than most Euro lagers available at the LCBO.

750 ml bottle from LCBO.  Pours murky yellow with a small head. Aroma of  strong fruity/citrus along with some yeast.  Flavour a citrus and yeast along with some spice, finishes nice.  Overall a great beer.
Had this one on tap at a club Nava in Markham (thanks Eelizis!)  Very malty aroma, sweet start not much on the palate.  A bit of a weak finish.  Typically something youd expect from Sleeman.

Bro bought me a 20 pack of Red/White over the holidays.  Hadnt tried the white yet so I got one to rate. Pours cloudy yellow, some citrus aroma, weak finish.  Not the best example of a Belgian wit but decent considering its from Molson.

330ml bottle, LCBO. Pours almost completely black.  Aroma of dark chocolate and fruits.  Nice roasty taste to begin with and a rich well rounded finish, though on some sips the alcohol was a tad overpowering.
500 ml can, LCBO.  Pours copper brown.  Straight up grainy aroma.  Malty flavour with a touch of bitterness in the end.  Pretty decent.
500 ml can, LCBO. Pours light yellow.  Smells like sour wet cardboard, tastes the same.  For a light pale Euro lager this one is pretty bad.

2nd last bottle of my six pack from 9 months ago sitting in my basement.  Figured the autumn months is best time to have this one.  Poured into my Chimay glass; brown with a thin tan head. Aroma a grape/raisin, with some spices, malt and alcohol. Flavour of dark fruits and spice - mostly nutmeg and clove, with some yeast in there as well.  Finishes very smooth.

Lucky enough to find a couple of singles at the LCBO, they jacked up the price of a six pack for this.  Nonetheless, great beer, pours amber with a tan head, lots of lacing.  Excellent citrus / hoppy aroma.  Not as hoppy a finish as the Dogfish Head Ive been having earlier, but I find it does have a nice balance.  Glad to have gems like this at the LCBO once in while.
